library(tidyverse)
library(nycflights13)

3.8.1

  1. This is an example of overplotting. So it under represents how many points are actually at each spot. I would use geom_jitter to show a better representation.

rr ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + geom_jitter()

  1. The paramters of geom_jitter that control the amount of jittering are width and height.
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_jitter(width = 9, height = 0)
  1. geom_count gives us different sized points depending on the amount of overlapping points. Both methods are ways to better view overlapping points. geom_count might have an area that has a large amount of points that can cover other points though, so it might not always be better to use it.
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_count()

  1. The default position for geom_boxpot is dodge. As you can see below, the plots look the same with and without position = "dodge".
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = fl, y = cty), position = "dodge")

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = fl, y = cty))

3.9.1

  1. labs() allows you to modify the title, axis, legend, and plot labels. You can rename them.

  2. The plot shows there is positive correlation between a car’s city mpg and highway mpg.
    As you can see without the coord_fixed() the x-axis distances are not the same as y-axis distances, so it can skew how people interpret data. Without coord_fixed() it looks like the city mpg increases faster than highway mpg.
    geom_abline adds in a line based on the parameters you enter into slope and intercept. As default, it makes the intercept = 0 and slope = 1. You can use it as a reference line when comparing the rest of the plot.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_abline() +
  coord_fixed()

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_abline()
